body:
I have a bidirectional pad model:

```verilog
module pad_model_bd ( 
    output logic RX_OUT, //% digital side Receive output <- input from PAD
    input wire TX_IN,  //% digital side Transmit value -> output to PAD
    input wire RXEN,  //% digital side Receive enable
    input wire TXEN,  //% digital side Transmit enable

    inout wire PAD, //% Pad connection

    inout wire PWROK,
    // verilator lint_off UNUSEDSIGNAL
    inout wire VDDIO,
    inout wire VDD,
    inout wire VSSIO,
    inout wire VSS
    // verilator lint_on UNUSEDSIGNAL
);

    // Require access to these variables for testing output
    logic PAD_txen;
    logic PAD_txout;
    always_comb begin
        PAD_txen  = (TXEN & PWROK);
        PAD_txout = (PAD_txen) ? TX_IN : 1'b0;
    end

    // Tried this but it doesn't allow a value to be set to pad i.e. m_dut->PAD = 0 doesn't propagate a value on PAD -> RXOUT
    // always PAD = (PAD_txen) ? TX_IN : 1'bz;

    // Input logic
    always_comb begin
        if (RXEN & PWROK) begin
            RX_OUT = PAD;
        end else begin
            RX_OUT = 1'b0;
        end
    end

    // Workaround to allow me to access what the pad output would be.
    export "DPI-C" task pad_bd_getPadOut;

    task pad_bd_getPadOut(output bit value, output bit enable);
        enable = PAD_txen;
        value  = PAD_txout;
    endtask

endmodule
```

So using this model - I can always access what would have been placed on the PAD output via the `pad_bd_getPadOut` DPI task - yes I know all the issues related to accessing this and not knowing when, but I have a scenario where the testbench in C++ land is the controller of sequencing, so I can access the task at known times (i.e. when things are settled and not at an edge).

However when I wrap this within a couple levels of hierarchy- note the example level of hierarchy below is verilog and not SystemVerilog and are written in this manner (not identifying wires/logic/regs because they are the models from a third-party vendor that I'm trying to mimic for behavioral sims in verilator).

```verilog
module wrapper_pad_bd ( RX_OUT,  PAD, DRV, TX_IN, RXEN, TXEN, PWROK, VDDIO, VDD, VSSIO, VSS );
output RX_OUT;
input TX_IN;
input RXEN;
input TXEN;

inout PAD;
inout PWROK;

inout VDDIO;
inout VDD;
inout VSSIO;
inout VSS;

    pad_model_bd verilator_model (
       .RX_OUT(RX_OUT),
       .TX_IN(TX_IN),
       .RXEN(RXEN),
       .TXEN(TXEN),
       .PAD(PAD),
       .PWROK(PWROK),
       .VDDIO(VDDIO),
       .VDD(VDD),
       .VSSIO(VSSIO),
       .VSS(VSS)
    );

endmodule
```

The PAD port when setting a value on it via C++  eg `m_dut->PAD = 1` - does not propagate to the lower level of hierarchy.

So I'm wondering what fundamental thing am I missing?

Example of pad_model_bd - checking RX_OUT logic (no wrapper):  Eg TOP->pad_model_bd
![image](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/assets/25964523/29b738f9-d093-450e-9770-84276387ce47)

Example of pad_model_bd - checking RX_OUT logic (no wrapper - but with `always PAD = (PAD_txen) ? TX_IN : 1'bz;` un-commented).
![image](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/assets/25964523/78ad2259-22f0-451b-896a-424190fcc708)
Notice PAD never gets the value pushed via a `m_dut->PAD = 0 / 1` from the C++ testbench.

So a similar thing happens when I have multiple levels of hierarchy as well.  The toplevel net/ port name has a value changing but all layers of hierarchy do not.

I'm at a point where I think I'll have to make a DPI-C function for the input PAD -> RX_OUT as well at this point.  And forget checking the connectivity of the very top to the PAD inout value.

Appreciate the help.
